[{"id":30719,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["Tasteless gas","Odourless gas","Colourless gas","Non-inflammable gas"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;Is the&nbsp;lightest element ever and is a&nbsp;tasteless, odourless, colourless, and highly combustible gas.&nbsp;It&#39;s also in most organic compounds</p><p>Hydrogen is a highly inflammable gas. This is because it burns in air to give water.&nbsp;</p><p>The reaction is as follows:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8203;</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8203;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8203;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30672,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["reacts vigorously than hydrogen","reacts just as hydrogen","emits <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;particles","reacts slower than hydrogen"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Reactivity of Deuterium is less than hydrogen due to high bond dissociation energy of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>Bond dissociation:<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>435</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>88</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>443</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>35</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Energy <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>kJ</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mole</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30673,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>)</mo></math> are true and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is the true explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is false.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is false but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is true.","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>)</mo></math> are true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is not the true explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>.</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Statement-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo></math> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> is used as a moderator in nuclear reactor and in exchange reactions for the study of reaction mechanisms.<br />Statement-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo></math> Bond energy of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&#60;</mo></math> Bond energy of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>.<br />So rate of reaction of cleavage of O-H bond is faster than that of O-D bond.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30657,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Hydrogen peroxide&nbsp;acts as an oxidising as well as reducing agent in both acidic and alkaline media.</p><p>But its reducing action is more effective in alkaline medium</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>KIO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow></mrow></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><msubsup><mi>KIO</mi><mn>3</mn><mrow></mrow></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>The oxidation number of iodine in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>IO</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math>&nbsp;is +5</p><p>The geometry of iodine containing compound changes from tetrahedral to pyramidal in the above reaction</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30666,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mg</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>MgCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ca</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>MgCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ca</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mg</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>During boiling&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mg</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>HCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is converted to insoluble&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mg</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mg</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>HCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Boiling</mi></mover><mi>Mg</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8595;</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ca</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>HCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>boiling</mi></mover><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8595;</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ca</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>HCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;changes to insoluble&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>Mg(OH)<sub>2​</sub>&nbsp;is less soluble than&nbsp;MgCO<sub>3.&nbsp;</sub>Hence, the products formed are CaCO<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;and Mg(OH)<sub>2</sub>.​</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30664,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HOCl</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PbS</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>PbSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msubsup><mi>MnO</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>MnO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Mn</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><msup><mi>Mn</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In option <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;reducing action of hydrogen peroxide is shown.</p><p>For reducing ability <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> changes to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>, i.e. oxidize, so in option &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; &amp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><none></none><mo>&#39;</mo><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mo>&#39;</mo></mmultiscripts><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>is formed but &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; is in acidic medium so option - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>&nbsp;is correct.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msubsup><mi>MnO</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>MnO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30714,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["Protium, deuterium and tritium","Tritium and protium only","Protium and deuterium only","Deuterium and tritium only"],"answer":0,"solution":"Isotopes have same atomic number and different atomic mass i.e., Same number of proton different number of Neutron relative atomic mass<br /><br />Protium&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><none/><mn>1</mn><mprescripts/><mn>1</mn><none/></mmultiscripts><mtable><mtr/></mtable></math><br /><br />Deuterium&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><none/><mn>2</mn><mprescripts/><mn>1</mn><none/></mmultiscripts></math><br /><br />Tritium&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><none/><mn>3</mn><mprescripts/><mn>1</mn><none/></mmultiscripts></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30712,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math><mn>2</mn></math> and <math><mn>1</mn></math>","<math><mn>2</mn></math>  and  <math><mn>0</mn></math>","<math><mn>3</mn></math> and <math><mn>1</mn></math>","<math><mn>3</mn></math>  and  <math><mn>2</mn></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Hydrogen is the first element in the periodic table&nbsp;and has the atomic number one. Those elements which have the same atomic number but a different mass number are called isotopes. There are three isotopes of hydrogen namely, protium <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mprescripts/><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mmultiscripts></math>, deuterium <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mprescripts/><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mmultiscripts></math>&nbsp;or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>&nbsp;and lastly tritium <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mprescripts/><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mmultiscripts></math>&nbsp;or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>. The isotopes are different because of the different number of neutrons present in them.</p><p>Isotopes of Hydrogen:<br /><br /><img height=\"70\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/40494040-53e7-4042-9313-3569e348a860-image.png\" width=\"243\" /><br /><br />Among all three isotopes only Tritium is radioactive.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30722,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{MnO}_4^{-}$","$\\mathrm{Cr}_2 \\mathrm{O}_7^{2-}$","$\\mathrm{SO}_3^{2-}$","KI"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}_2$ acts as a reducing agent only in presence of strong oxidising agents (i.e., $\\left.\\mathrm{MnO}_4^{-}\\right)$in acidic as well as alkaline medium.\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n&2 \\mathrm{KMnO}_4+3 \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{SO}_4+5 \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}_2 \\longrightarrow \\\\\n&\\mathrm{K}_2 \\mathrm{SO}_4+2 \\mathrm{MnSO}_4+8 \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}+5 \\mathrm{O}_2\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30708,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math><mn>90</mn></math>  ppm","<math><mn>50</mn></math>  ppm","<math><mn>10</mn></math>  ppm","<math><mn>100</mn></math> ppm"],"answer":3,"solution":"As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math>&nbsp;solution have <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>mol</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub><mi>CaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Eq</mi><mo>.</mo><mtext>&#8201;&#8201;</mtext><mi>of</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub><mi>CaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>eq</mi><mo>.</mo><mtext>&#8201;&#8201;</mtext><mi>of</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math><br /><br />In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math> solution<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><msub><mi>CaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>.</mo></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>mol</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>in</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mtext>&#8201;&#8201;</mtext></math> in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math> solution<br /><br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> hardness in terms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><msub><mi>CaCO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mi>total</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ppm</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30671,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d3033c46-edda-4d8b-a675-02cd8baa8ca8-image.png\" style=\"width: 574px; height: 265px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30676,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cr</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mn</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Co</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Elements of group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>9</mn></math>&nbsp;do not form hydrides thus Cr will only form hydride among the given<br />elements <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>Fe</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Mn</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Co</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30726,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CO}$ and $\\mathrm{H}_2$ are fractionally separated using differences in their densities","$\\mathrm{CO}$ is removed by absorption in aqueous $\\mathrm{Cu}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}_2$ solution","$\\mathrm{H}_2$ is removed through occlusion with $\\mathrm{Pd}$","$\\mathrm{CO}$ is oxidised to $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ with steam in the presence of a catalyst followed by absorption of $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ in alkali"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/82USX_GKB-_cCCiRoRxi1Kik7zxc0wtajHJULGbAZL4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":30675,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mtext>&#160;and&#160;</mtext><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mtext>&#160;and&#160;</mtext><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mtext>&#160;and&#160;</mtext><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mtext>&#160;and&#160;</mtext><mn>2</mn></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"Radioactive isotope of hydrogen is Tritium <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mmultiscripts><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></mrow><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mmultiscripts></mfenced></math><br />No. of neutrons <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Z</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br />No. of electrons <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30713,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CaCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ca</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>HCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math> ions are the cause of permanent hardness &amp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>HCO</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math> ions are the cause of temporary Hardness.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30643,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<p>Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are correct and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","<p>A is correct but R is not correct</p>","<p>A is not correct but R is correct</p>","<p>Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NOT</mi></math> the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Loss of an electron from a hydrogen atom results in a nucleus of very small size as compared to other atoms or ions. Due to its small size it cannot exist free.&nbsp;Loss of the electron from hydrogen atom results in nucleus size (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>) of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></math></p><p>A proton is a positively charged subatomic particle that is present in the nucleus of an atom, and it can exist in various forms, including as a part of an atomic nucleus, as a free particle, or as a constituent of a larger particle such as a molecule.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;always exists in combined form.</p></blockquote><p>Both A and R are correct but there is no relation between two statements.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30651,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Li</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SiH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaNi</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>","Di-isobutylaluminium hydride"],"answer":2,"solution":"Dihydrogen&nbsp;gas is converted into liquid state by cooling to 20K. This would require expensive insulated tanks. Tanks are metal alloy like&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaNi</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Ti</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>TiH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Mg</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>MgH</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;etc. are in use for storage of dihydrogen.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30685,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Sb</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>As</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Bi</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mo>]</mo><mprescripts></mprescripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mmultiscripts><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>&nbsp;Non-metal</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mo>]</mo><mprescripts></mprescripts><mi>Sb</mi><mi>As</mi></mmultiscripts><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>&nbsp;Metalloid</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mi>Bi</mi><mo>]</mo></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>&nbsp;Metal</p><p>Hydrides of group 15 elements are</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AsH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SbH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BiH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>, hydrogen atom gets partial positive charge due to less electronegativity. But in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BiH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>, hydrogen atom gets partial negative charge because hydrogen is more electronegative than bismuth.</p><p>i.e. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BiH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is a strong reducing agent than others because we know that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math> is a strong reducing agent.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30699,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math><mi>a</mi></math>","<math><mi>a</mi></math> and <math><mi>d</mi></math>","<math><mi>c</mi></math> and <math><mi>d</mi></math>","<math><mi>d</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"In blast furnace (metallugy of iron) involved<br />reactions are<br />&nbsp;<math> <mo stretchy='false'>(</mo><mtext>a</mtext><mo stretchy='false'>)</mo><mtext>&#x2009;</mtext><mtext>CaO</mtext><mo>+</mo><msub>  <mtext>SiO</mtext>  <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>&#x2192;</mo><msub>  <mtext>CaSiO</mtext>  <mn>3</mn> </msub> </math><br><br><math > <mo stretchy='false'>(</mo><mtext>b</mtext><mo stretchy='false'>)</mo><mtext>&#x2009;</mtext><mn>3</mn><msub>  <mtext>Fe</mtext>  <mn>2</mn> </msub> <msub>  <mtext>O</mtext>  <mn>3</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo><mtext>CO</mtext><mo>&#x2192;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub>  <mtext>Fe</mtext>  <mn>3</mn> </msub> <msub>  <mtext>O</mtext>  <mn>4</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo><msub>  <mtext>CO</mtext>  <mn>2</mn> </msub> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30638,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["A-III, B-II, C-IV, D-I","A-II, B-III, C-I, D-IV","A-II, B-III, C-IV, D-I","A-III, B-II, C-I, D-IV"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math>, known as diborane, is an example of an electron-deficient hydride.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HF</mi></math>, or hydrogen fluoride, is an example of an electron-rich hydride. Electron-rich hydrides are molecules that contain more electrons than what would be expected based on the normal valence electron count for the atoms involved.&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is electrons precise hydride since, there are exact number of electrons to form normal covalent bonds for completing octet.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>MgH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is salline hydride, as this is the hydride&nbsp;that formed when hydrogen reacts with s-Block elements.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">A</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Electron deficient hydride</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">III</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">B</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Electron rich hydride</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">II</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HF</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">C</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Electron precise hydride</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">IV</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">D</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Saline hydride</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">I</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>MgH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30679,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["(A),(C) only","(A) only","(B) only","(A), (B) only"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In basic medium, oxidising action of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Mn</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><msup><mi>Mn</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p><p>In basic medium, reducing action of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>In acidic medium, oxidising action of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PbS</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>PbSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Hence correct option <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>)</mo></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30710,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["$Electron-rich hydride$","$Metallic hydride$","$Saline hydride$","$Molecular hydride$"],"answer":2,"solution":"NaH is an ionic hydride which is also known as saline hydride.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30644,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>- shorter, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>-</mo></math> shorter","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>-shorter, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>-longer","&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>-longer, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>-longer","&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>-longer,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math> - shorter"],"answer":3,"solution":"According to bent rule more electronegative atom occupy less s-character so bond length increases. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> bond will be short than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math> bond due to small size of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math>. Correspondingly,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;bond in hydrogen peroxide will be shorter than that of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>. Corresponding structures are:<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c2ab2c9b-5f84-44c3-8249-b441bd80c491-26.PNG\" style=\"width: 273px; height: 282px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30718,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["There is extensive intramolecular hydrogen bonding in the condensed phase.","Ice formed by heavy water sinks in normal water.","Water is oxidized to oxygen during photosynthesis","Water can act both as an acid and as a base"],"answer":0,"solution":"(i) Ice formed by heavy water sinks in normal water due to higher density of <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> than normal water.<br /><br />(ii) <math> <mrow>  <mn>6</mn><msub>   <mrow>    <mtext>CO</mtext></mrow>   <mn>2</mn>  </msub>  <mo>+</mo><mtext>&#x2009;</mtext><mn>6</mn><msub>   <mtext>H</mtext>   <mn>2</mn>  </msub>  <mtext>O</mtext><munderover>   <mo>&#x2192;</mo>   <mrow>    <mtext>chlorophyll</mtext></mrow>   <mrow>    <mtext>hv</mtext></mrow>  </munderover>  <msub>   <mtext>C</mtext>   <mtext>6</mtext>  </msub>  <msub>   <mtext>H</mtext>   <mrow>    <mtext>12</mtext></mrow>  </msub>  <msub>   <mtext>O</mtext>   <mtext>6</mtext>  </msub>  <msub>   <mrow>    <mtext>+6O</mtext></mrow>   <mtext>2</mtext>  </msub>  </mrow></math><br /><br />(iii) Water can show amphiprotic nature and hence water can act both as an acid a base.<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aqz.JPG\" style=\"width: 321px; height: 146px;\" /><br />(iv) There is extensive intermolecular hydrogen bonding in the condensed phase instead of intramolecular H - bonding.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30715,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>and</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>and</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>and</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>and</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Hydrogen undergoes the following changes:</p><p>1) While acting as an&nbsp;oxidising agent in an acidic medium,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>2) While acting as a reducing agent in an alkaline medium,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow></mrow></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30721,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["It has to be kept away from dust.","It can act only as an oxidising agent.","It decomposes on exposure to light.","It has to be stored in plastic or wax-lined glass bottles in the dark."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>It can act both as an oxidizing agent and a reducing agent. The reason is the oxidation state of &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&#39;&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30707,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math><mn>5.6</mn></math>","<math><mn>22.4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>11.2</mn></math>","<math><mn>16.8</mn></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math><msub><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mtext>O</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mtext>O&#160;</mtext><mo>+</mo></math> <math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mtext>O</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Volume strength</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>11.2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mtext>Molarity</mtext></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>11.2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>11.2</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30709,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["$(ii) and (iv) only$","$(i) and (iii) only$","$(ii), (iii) and (iv) only$","$(i), (ii) and (iii) only$"],"answer":3,"solution":"option (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30678,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is not correct.","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is not the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>.</mo></math>","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are correct and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is not correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is correct."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/24189c93-847f-4214-b550-61eb57732333-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 189px;\" /></p><p>(a) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> structure in gas phase, dihedral angle is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>111</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>. (b) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> structure in solid phase at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>110</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math>, dihedral angle is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>90</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>. Hence given statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is not correct But statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is correct.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30705,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrogen","question":"","options":["<math><mn>1.7</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>13.6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>34</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>3.4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Molarity of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>Volume</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8201;</mi><mi>strength</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>11</mn><mo>.2</mo></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>11.2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>11.2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> <math><mn>1</mn></math> molar means <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1000</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>mL</mi></math> solution contains&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8201;</mo><mi>mol</mi><mo>&#8201;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>34</mn><mi>&#8201;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p>Since, the strength is represented as weight of the solute in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math> of the solution. The strength of the solution will be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>34</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p><p>Note: The question should&#39;ve mentioned that we need to find the mass by volume percentage.</p><p>Percentage w/v&nbsp;<math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>34</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1000</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>3.4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null}]